description: Friendica is a decentralized, self-hostable alternative to Facebook. It has all the basic Facebook functionality (pages, groups, events), and also some neat little features like formatting (using BBCode), a calendar, a dislike button on posts and comments, post titles and other stuff that Meta did not add to it to this day. Friendica is multiprotocol (i.e. supports both ActivityPub and the diaspora protocols) and extensible, with add-ons that allow you to connect to other networks like Bluesky or Tumblr. Friendica also allows you to follow the websites' RSS feeds like regular accounts, with each article posted via RSS appearing in the regular feed.

The search engine is also family-friendly, filtering out explicit content to ensure a safe browsing experience for users of all ages. Swisscows operates under strict data privacy laws and is based in Switzerland, with servers located in underground data centers under the Swiss Alps, geographically outside of the EU and US. Swisscows is available as a default search engine option in various browsers and has a mobile app for convenient use.

name: Asphalte
description: Asphalte is a clothing company that produces wardrobe staples for men and women using a pre-order model to reduce waste and focus on durable, responsibly made garments.
Notes for mods:
We're not into mass-producing stuff you don't need. On the contrary, we want to tailor our products to you and manufacture them on demand:

Co-creation. You decide from A to Z. Collection plan, cut, colours, materials: we don't do anything until you give us the go-ahead. In fact, that's what our famous questionnaires and the 'co-creation' tab in the menu is all about.
Preordering. It's simple: your purchase triggers the production process. You waiting a few weeks means that we avoid overproduction and logistical costs. We invest the money saved to provide you with the best raw materials and European know-how at the best possible price.
After analysing your responses to the co-creation questionnaires, our product team takes over. Here's how it works:

Our stylists design the garment. They combine your feedback with vintage samples to reproduce details and finishes that have lasted through the decades.
The product development team finds and tests the best materials with an independent third party lab. After that, they knuckle down on the fit and find the perfect balance between comfort and durability
We collectively flesh out the project to get a good idea of the final result. If we're convinced, we launch prototyping with our production partners and keep developing them until we have the perfect result. This has been known to take up to two years. Ultimate Jeans anyone?
The material is bought, the patterns are ready, the machines are set up, the launch is scheduled. That's it, we can finally open the preorder campaign.

This happens every Tuesday at 10:00 CET sharp. Every week at this precise time, 52 weeks a year, a new product is available to preorder for 6 days only. So each Sunday at midnight, we close a preorder and start counting up the quantity to produce.

The timing may seem tight, but it's the best we've come up with to streamline shipments and deliver to you right at the right time of year.

Once your order has been confirmed and the preorder have closed, our partner factories get busy producing your item. This takes a few weeks, sometimes longer, but we think it‚Äôs worth it to get the best level of quality for this price. And more and more people seem to agree.

name: DBMail
description: DBMail is an open-source message delivery agent that uses industry-standard protocols like IMAP, POP, ManageSieve, and LMTP. It stores emails in databases such as PostgreSQL, MySQL, and Oracle, providing a scalable and secure solution for managing user emails. DBMail is designed to integrate with existing authentication backends like ActiveDirectory and OpenLDAP, making it suitable for large-scale deployments. It supports features like email filtering using SIEVE and offers high availability through database replication and Docker images.
Notes for mods: Hi, I'm Alan Hicks ahicks@p-o.co.uk from Persistent Objects in London and I'm the maintainer for DBMail. It was started in 1999 by IC&S in the Netherlands.

Matrix is decentralized, meaning users can host their own servers and control their data, ensuring privacy and security through end-to-end encryption. You can download softwares and mobile apps to start communicating.
